bioghist.head: Biographical / Historical
bioghist.p: Henry G. Kunkel (1916-1983) was an immunologist and clinical investigator who was one of the earliest practitioners in the field of clinical immunology. He spent the majority of his career at The Rockefeller University (formerly the Rockefeller Institute for Medical Research), beginning there as an Assistant Professor in 1945. In the early part of his career, he focused on basic immunology, using myeloma proteins to decipher the chain structure of immunoglobulins and antibodies. This work allowed for the first mapping of immunoglobulin genes to their respective chromosomes and the classification of antibodies.

In the latter part of his career, Dr. Kunkel focused primarily on the clinical investigation end of immunology. This included making significant strides in the studies of diseases such as systemic lupus erythematosus, rheumatoid arthritis, and chronic liver disease, as well as lymphoproliferative diseases (production of excessive quantities of lymphocytes) and primary immunodeficiency disorders (where parts of the body's immune system are missing or not functioning properly). He was also an editor of the Journal of Experimental Medicine from 1960 until his death, and a co-founding editor of Advances in Immunology. Dr. Kunkel died on December 15, 1983.

September 9, 1916: Born in Brooklyn, New York to noted botanist Louis O. Kunkel (a member of the Rockefeller Institute) and horticulturist Joanna Kunkel. 1938-Graduated from Princeton University with a B.A. 1942-Graduated from Johns Hopkins University with an M.D. July 1942-March 1943-Intern at Bellevue Hospital March-August 1943-Assistant Resident at Bellevue Hospital August 1943-July 1946-Served in the Medical Corps of the U.S. Naval Research. Included active service in Italy. March 1945-December 1983-Appointed as a member of the Rockefeller Institute for Medical Research in 1945, he later became a full member in 1952. Concurrently, he was also promoted from Assistant Resident Physician at The Rockefeller University Hospital to Physician. July 1950-June 1951-Visiting Investigator, Biochemical Institute (Uppsala, Sweden) 1973-1983-Adjunct Professor of Medicine at Cornell University Medical School (New York, New York) 1975-Received the Albert Lasker Basic Medical Research Award for contributions to the field of immunology, in particular to the understanding of how harmful imunologic responses can cause injury and disease, through his work with rheumatoid arthritis and kidney disease. 1976-1983-Abby Rockefeller Mauze Professor at The Rockefeller University 1977-Received the Louisa Gross Horwitz Prize for Biology or Biochemistry. It was awarded for his work in extending the study of immunology by creating the groundwork for a classification of immunoglobulins, as well as his work with rheumatoid arthritis and lupus erythematosus. December 15, 1983-Died in New York.

separatedmaterial.head: Separated Materials
separatedmaterial.p: Some items in this collection were separated into other collections at the Archive Center:
Photographs: Some photographs were removed before the collection was processed and incorporated into the Rockefeller University collection- RG1100 Photographs.
Books: These have been removed from the collection and added to the Rockefeller Archive Center library.
Instrument Catalogs: Added to the Rockefeller University collection-RG 851 Instrument and Equipment Catalogs.

Rockefeller University Publications: Consists of annual reports, News and Notes, and various other University-related publciations. These were removed and incorporporated into the appropriate collections.

scopecontent.p: Types of records include: biographical material, correspondence, notes, subject files, photographs, negatives, slides, reprints, and ephemera.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Includes a bibliography of Dr. Kunkel as well as a number of biographical sources. Also includes: certificates, correspondence related to awards he received, administrative correspondence related to his appointments and promotions. There aer some photographs of both Dr. Kunkel and his laboratory at the Rockefeller University.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Contains bound notebooks and loose notes written by Dr. Kunkel and his laboratory staff at the Rockefeller University. Subjects include: hemoglobins, immunofluorescence, lymphocytes, and monoclonal antibodies. There are also a number of notebooks that are listed solely by numbers or which are untitled. Some files are closed because they contain files of a sensitive nature, primarily identifiable patient information.
